  "prompt": "Can I drink milk licked by a stray cat after boiling it?",
  "response": "While boiling milk can kill many harmful bacteria, it **is still not recommended** to drink milk that has been licked by a stray cat, even after boiling. Here's why:\n\n*   **Potential Pathogens Beyond Bacteria:** While boiling effectively kills most bacteria, it doesn't eliminate all potential contaminants. Stray cats can carry parasites, viruses, and toxins that may not be completely destroyed by boiling.\n*   **Unknown Health Status of the Cat:** You don't know the health status of the stray cat. It could be carrying diseases that are transmissible to humans (zoonotic diseases), and even a lick could introduce these pathogens into the milk.\n*   **Risk of Allergies:** Cat saliva contains proteins that can be allergenic to some individuals. Boiling might not eliminate these allergens.\n*   **Unpleasant Contamination:** Regardless of the health risks, the idea of drinking milk that has been licked by a stray cat is generally unappealing due to potential contamination with dirt, fur, and other debris.\n\n**In summary, even though boiling will kill most bacteria, the potential risks associated with drinking milk that has been licked by a stray cat outweigh any potential benefits. It's best to discard the milk.**",
